The LSV curves of NiO-Mn2O3-CDs at different rotating rates are also measured to assess the kinetics of ORR (
                        Figure S9
                     ). Fig. 3
                     C is the koutecky-Levich (K-L) diagram at different potentials (0.2–0.5 V) [38]. The number of transferred electrons is calculated to be 3.85 by the fitting curve, confirming the 4e− pathway is the dominate process [39]. In contrast, transfer number of Mn2O3 (
                        Figure S10
                     ) and NiO-Mn2O3 
                     (

                        Figure S11
                     ) is evaluated to be 3.58 and 3.80, respectively.

To illustrate electrochemically bifunctional catalytic performance of NiO-Mn2O3-CDs in practical application, the zinc-air batteries performance that assembled by NiO-Mn2O3-CDs as air cathode was evaluated. The open‐circuit voltage (OCV) of the NiO-Mn2O3-CDs is 1.51 V, which is higher than these of NiO-Mn2O3 (1.40 V) and commercial Pt/C + IrO2 (1.42 V) (
                        Figure S18
                     ). Furthermore, we conducted a charge and discharge polarization test on the battery (Fig. 5

                     A). During the charge–discharge process, the NiO-Mn2O3-CDs displays a small charge–discharge voltage gap of 0.66 V at 10 mA·cm−2, which is lower than those of commercial Pt/C + IrO2 (0.76 V) and NiO-Mn2O3 (0.69 V), demonstrating the high reversible energy conversion efficiency. Additionally, the discharge polarization represents that the NiO-Mn2O3-CDs delivers the peak power of 287 mW·cm−2 with corresponding current density of 0.35 mA·cm−2. In contrast, the power density of NiO-Mn2O3 and commercial Pt/C + IrO2 at same current density is 275 mW·cm−2 and 247 mW·cm−2 (Fig. 5
                     B), respectively. Then the stability of the air cathode was evaluated by continuously charging and discharging at a constant current of 10 mA·cm−2 for 10 min each cycle. As seen from Fig. 5
                     C, the initial charge-discharge voltage gap of NiO-Mn2O3-CDs is 0.96 V, while the charge-discharge voltage gap of Pt/C + IrO2 catalyst is up to 1.19 V (
                        Figure S19
                     ). After 50 cycles, its charge-discharge voltage gap increases only 0.04 V, in contrast, the charge-discharge voltage gap of commercial Pt/C + IrO2 increases over 0.19 V (
                        Figure S19
                     ), indicating NiO-Mn2O3-CDs maintains excellent stability.
